
[1]emaciate

   EMA'CIATE, v.i. [L. emacio, from maceo, or macer, lean; Gr. small; Eng.
   meager, meek.] To lose flesh gradually; to become lean by pining with
   sorrow, or by loss of appetite or other cause; to waste away, as flesh;
   to decay in flesh.

   EMA'CIATE, v.t. To cause to lose flesh gradually; to waste the flesh
   and reduce to leanness.

   Sorrow, anxiety, want of appetite, and disease, often emaciate the most
   robust bodies.
